{"type":"assistant","uuid":"cda0951d-2061-4529-96d6-879cf0a7b862","session_id":"46cb52b0-1daf-4d80-90ef-52f48adf4b51","message":{"id":"cda0951d-2061-4529-96d6-879cf0a7b862","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user has provided a detailed clinical scenario. Let me analyze the patient information:\n\n**Patient:** P0000456, 23-year-old male, 张*\n**Chief Complaint:** 上腹部疼痛伴恶心呕吐 2 天 (epigastric pain with nausea and vomiting for 2 days)\n**Present Illness:** 2 days ago after eating large amount of spicy hot pot + ice beer, developed continuous epigastric dull pain, with nausea, vomited gastric contents 3-4 times, no hematemesis or melena. No chronic gastric history, no recent alcohol (only that night) or medication history.\n**Physician Diagnosis:** K29.1 急性单纯性胃炎（理化因素刺激所致）(Acute simple gastritis due to physical/chemical irritation)\n\n**Physical Exam:**\n- Abdomen: 上腹部压痛阳性，无反跳痛及肌紧张 (epigastric tenderness positive, no rebound tenderness or guarding)\n- Bowel sounds: 肠鸣音正常 (normal)\n- Consciousness: 清醒 (alert)\n- Vomitus: 胃内容物，无血液无咖啡渣样物 (gastric contents, no blood or coffee-ground appearance)\n\n**Vitals:** BP 126/78, Pulse 88, RR 18, SpO2 98%, Temp 36.9°C\n\n**Labs:** \n- WBC 8.2 (normal)\n- Neut% 65% (normal)\n→ No evidence of bacterial infection\n\n**Allergies:** None\n**Comorbidities:** None\n**Current medications:** None\n**Renal function:** eGFR 108, CrCl 115 (normal)\n**Hepatic function:** normal\n**Pregnancy:** none (male)\n\n**Assessment:**\nThis is a young male with acute simple gastritis caused by dietary indiscretion (spicy hot pot + ice beer). \n\nThe clinical picture is straightforward - acute gastritis from dietary triggers with no signs of infection, no red flags, and no complications. Given the normal labs and physical exam, this appears to be uncomplicated acute gastritis that should respond to symptomatic treatment with acid suppression and anti-emetics. No antibiotics needed since there's no infectious etiology. The patient can likely be managed with a short course of PPI and perhaps an anti-emetic if nausea persists. I should consider what medications are appropriate here and check their availability through the API.\n\nFor acute gastritis, the standard approach would be acid suppression (PPI like omeprazole or pantoprazole), and possibly an anti-emetic (metoclopramide or domperidone) if nausea is significant. I also need to consider mucosal protectants like sucralfate, though PPI alone is often sufficient. Let me look up the drug information through the API to confirm what's available and appropriate.","signature":""}],"model":"hy3-preview-ioa","role":"assistant","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"type":"message","usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":null,"cache_read_input_tokens":null,"cache_creation":null,"server_tool_use":null,"service_tier":null}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"__timestamp":"2026-05-31T04:58:52.964Z","_requestId":"ce6a2a65fcf54653bf33f6a2f031bb71"}
